The fall womens tennis season officially came to a close last weekend but for two of the players the competition is not yet complete PERIOD

Tammy OkinsNguyen and Kerri Kohr will travel to the University of Pennsylvania this weekend to compete in the Rolex Intercollegiate Tennis Coaches Association Championships PERIOD Both will compete in singles competition and will then team up for doubles in the tournament which begins at  Friday morning and ends Sunday evening PERIOD

 OkinsNguyen said PERIOD 

Both players have realistic hopes for the tournament because they are not familiar with their competition PERIOD They are not sure who will be there and who they will be competing against PERIOD

 Kohr said PERIOD 

Coach Sue Whiteside shares the same opinion on the importance of the tournament PERIOD She was hoping to send more players to the competition like her No PERIOD  doubles team Jennifer Farrington and Ann Slocomb but she will have to be satisfied with the top two players PERIOD

 Whiteside said PERIOD 

Over  Division I schools will be represented in the tournament which invites more than  competitors PERIOD The topseeded singles player is Julie Shiflet from William  Mary and the top doubles team consists of Pam Piorkowski and Jennifer Lane from Boston College PERIOD

 tournament director Cissie Leary said PERIOD 

The top two singles players and the No PERIOD  doubles team from the tournament will make it to nationals which will be held on Feb PERIOD  in Minneapolis Minn PERIOD
